Currently, Bitbucket blocks certain endpoints, like https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/rest/api-group-ssh/#api-users-selected-user-ssh-keys-get from being pulled by anyone except the owners of the Bitbucket account.

For example, when performing a request to this endpoint as an org admin that is not the owner of the target account, you will receive the following response:
{code}
{"type": "error", "error": {"message": "You cannot administer personal accounts of other users."}}
{code}

This behavior is expected for non-managed accounts, but for org-managed accounts, the organization admin should have the right to get information about their users, like when the key was created or how many keys does the user have.

This feature request is to add the ability to run API requests against Atlassian Access managed user accounts from your organization, if you are an org admin of that user's organization.

The following bucket is used to host and distribute malware.

[https://bitbucket.org/trustedrootdev/file/downloads/]

All the files hosted in the bucked are scrambled by just reversing the byte orders. The following pseudocode unscrambles the files and retrieves the malicious files.


{code:java}
// Byte array of a raw file.
let data_in = readFromFile('downloaded_file_path');

// Byte array holding the unscrambled file.
let data_out = Array(data_in.length);

for(let i = 0 ; i < data_in.length ; i++)
{
  data_out[i] = data_in[data_in.length - i - i];
}

writeToFile('/path/to/malware.dll', data_out);{code}

